					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/benji-the-benevolent" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6199018); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6199018&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164980" alt="Benji_the_Benevolent" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6199018)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/benji-the-benevolent" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6199018); return false;" >Benji_the_Benevolent</a></span> <span class="odate time_1594212972 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Jul 2020 12:56</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4713267">
									

<p>Hey, I'm not sure whether anyone will respond to this since the last post was 2 years ago! But I'll ask anyway.</p>
<p>This probably sounds pretty petty, and an easily changeable complaint but it happens quite often and it's so bothersome. It's really annoying (for me personally) when, not just staff, but any viewer who replies to a vague, incomplete review to a writer on the help idea critique, with</p>
<blockquote>
<p>this feedback is vague and unhelpful. As per the site's Criticism Policy, forum critique should be relatively in-depth. Staff prioritize threads with no response, and by offering poor critique, you may be preventing an author from receiving the critique they are seeking.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I understand that the person who gave the obscure review in the first place is definitely incorrect, but I would argue that the staff (let's just say staff for simplicity) is equally in the wrong, causing the exact problems the other reviewer is causing:</p>
<ul>
<li>Giving absolutely no response at all</li>
</ul>
<p>&amp;</p>
<ul>
<li>Adding to the amount of response, lessening the chance of writer getting responded to, even more than the different reviewer</li>
</ul>
<p>This hypocritical mindset is why I'm so irritated.</p>
<p>I believe if a member 'staff' doesn't have any review or input to give, then they should not reply at all. Sure, I'm fine if you complain to a vague response and add your reviews and opinions as well, but if you just leave a half-arse &quot;I am good! your response is bad!&quot; and no review (sorry for my bashful language), then that is disappointing to the writer who is actually waiting for a response and a review, buts accompanies a tv drama instead.</p>
<p>I'm sorry if I was extremely forward. But this was bothering me for a while and I feel this could have been an apparent fix.</p>

							</div>

								
