			<div class="content" id="post-content-4713856">
									

<p>As a general note, for this thread, please use the &quot;new post&quot; button at the bottom left of the screen&#8212;that way the comment will nest properly with the other newer comments. Typically when checking this thread, staff don't look at the first posts (which, if comments are posted correctly, are the oldest queries).</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>I understand that the person who gave the obscure review in the first place is definitely incorrect, but I would argue that the staff (let's just say staff for simplicity) is equally in the wrong, causing the exact problems the other reviewer is causing:</p>
<p>Giving absolutely no response at all</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What do you recommend that staff do instead to address problematic critique?</p>
<p>Also, if staff/reviewers should be obligated to provide a critique if they're going to comment on someone providing low-quality critique, what should be done to prevent authors from taking advantage of that and &quot;helping&quot; people get more reviews by spamposting low quality material on other threads?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Adding to the amount of response, lessening the chance of writer getting responded to, even more than the different reviewer</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The forum guidelines have changed, and reviews are no longer automatically given/prioritized to threads that have fewer replies. Rather, authors are asked to contact reviewers directly to request feedback.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Sure, I'm fine if you complain to a vague response and add your reviews and opinions as well, but if you just leave a half-arse &quot;I am good! your response is bad!&quot; and no review (sorry for my bashful language),</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This admittedly comes off as rather accusatory. If you feel that staff template responses sound like half-arsed complaining that targets users personally while making it seem like staff are self-congratulating, please provide examples of alternate wording that can be used for said templates.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>then that is disappointing to the writer who is actually waiting for a response and a review,</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Again, authors should reach out to reviewers to request feedback rather than just waiting without reaching out at all. We have a thread for this: <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-13282692/how-to-get-more-reviews">http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-13282692/how-to-get-more-reviews</a></p>
