<p>Hey Zyn, sorry for the last post it was&#8230; unprofessional,</p>
<p>Next time I will use the 'new post'. (I did wonder why the front page post was so far back.)</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Response</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Response</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>what should be done to prevent authors from taking advantage of that and &quot;helping&quot; people get more reviews by spamposting low quality material on other threads?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You're definitely right there, there's not really another way of replying to many short spam threads other than using short warnings, but I presume that you and the staff team can delete such responses and leave a verbal warning, which I'm fine about since these posts won't be about the bad reviews but the spamming its self.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The forum guidelines have changed, and reviews are no longer automatically given/prioritized to threads that have fewer replies. Rather, authors are asked to contact reviewers directly to request feedback.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I knew that from the start, although you still do both, take my example from before:<br />
<em>&quot;This feedback is vague and unhelpful. As per the site's Criticism Policy, forum critique should be relatively in-depth. Staff prioritize threads with no response, and by offering poor critique, you may be preventing an author from receiving the critique they are seeking.&quot;</em></p>
<p>This was a new response, on the help critique forums that if you scrolled 3 to 2 pages you'll probably find, so I simply assumed that this was still done. Plus for none staff reviewers, they do rely on 'no response threads' and newer works to critique.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This admittedly comes off as rather accusatory. If you feel that staff template responses sound like half-arsed complaining that targets users personally while making it seem like staff are self-congratulating, please provide examples of alternate wording that can be used for said templates.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Apologies for this, like I said &quot;Unprofessional.&quot; However my statement came out wrong, it's not that staff are blatantly screaming out of their lungs &quot;I am good! your response is bad!&quot; It's that hypocritical mindset that makes me believe with this statement. Notifying reviewers that their response didn't help the author in a sufficient way while replying with a message that doesn't help the author in any sufficient way, feels very one-sided. Even though the staff are doing the same thing as the bad reviewers, they're in the right?</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>All in all, I can already tell you won't budge and won't do anything about it. It's was only a minor critique anyway, sorry for wasting your time.</p>

