				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164980" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;" >Zyn</a></span> <span class="odate time_1594363741 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 Jul 2020 06:49</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4714903">
									

<p>Responses:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>I presume that you and the staff team can delete such responses and leave a verbal warning, which I'm fine about since these posts won't be about the bad reviews but the spamming its self.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Staff only delete posts that contain severe rulebreaking, to keep users accountable for what they post. Doing that also allows for greater transparency&#8212;just because staff know that a post was deleted doesn't mean that site members in general know that a post was removed.</p>
<p>Furthermore, users often create multiple &quot;replacement&quot; posts or threads when they think something they posted is missing. Dropping a staff warning doesn't always guarantee that spamming will stop, or that the spammer will notice the staff warnings to begin with.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This was a new response, on the help critique forums that if you scrolled 3 to 2 pages you'll probably find, so I simply assumed that this was still done.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Can you provide a direct link to the post? The forum threads shift fairly often day-to-day, so what you've seen on page 2-3 will definitely be different from what I'm seeing 19 hours later. If I know the staff member who's using an outdated placeholder, they can be updated much faster.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Plus for none staff reviewers, they do rely on 'no response threads' and newer works to critique.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Is this something that you can confirm with examples and comparisons? I've tended to see a more or less even split between newer reviewers responding to threads with no replies versus threads that already have replies. Again though, it might depend on the time of day that the forums are viewed.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>It's that hypocritical mindset that makes me believe with this statement. Notifying reviewers that their response didn't help the author in a sufficient way</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Newer placeholders should ideally implement the following link: <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-9804362/so-you-want-to-be-a-concept-reviewer">http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-9804362/so-you-want-to-be-a-concept-reviewer</a></p>
<p>Ideally, staff addressing problematic feedback should be encouraging the reviewer in question to improve their critique themselves, rather than expecting staff to essentially write one for them.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>while replying with a message that doesn't help the author in any sufficient way, feels very one-sided.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Are you stating that you feel that noting feedback is problematic does not help the author?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Even though the staff are doing the same thing as the bad reviewers, they're in the right?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Staff are inherently not &quot;doing the same thing as the bad reviewers&quot;, as they are present in the thread not to post a review, but to address breach of forum rules/etiquette. A reviewer who posts a low-quality review is not present in the thread to address any sort of forum guideline in the same capacity.</p>
<p>I think the disconnect here is the belief that if <em>anyone</em> posts in a review thread, for whatever reason, they're obligated to give a review. Is this correct?</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>ETA: also, as a general note, there's no need to sign your posts. Everyone can already see your username at the top of every comment you post, and this is a forum discussion, not an email chain. It seems a little silly to re-introduce yourself repeatedly when again, the associated username is fairly obvious.</p>

							</div>

								
