<h4><span>This discussion has been stop-ordered. Please see <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-5797485/complaints-thread#post-3829581">here</a> for further information. ~ Decibelle</span></h4>
<p>Since it's Pride Month, I see that the Foundation emblem at the top of the site page has been given a rainbow background. I understand and do not oppose the presumed sentiments or motives that led to this, but I do find it a bit immersion-breaking. There's a reason why even the disclaimer stating that the threat of detainment that appears in bold at the top of the main/front page is not a real warning only appears tucked away from the main/front page elsewhere on the site: immersion preservation.</p>
<p>Yes, I understand that there are plenty of other things that break immersion on the site and even on the main/front page. You would need to be pretty dimwitted to not notice many of these things even upon cursory examination. That being said, there is nothing so predominant on the screen that embraces its almost self-recognized immersion-breaking quality.</p>
<p>I ain't no homophobe, trust me. I just think that maybe the rainbow background to the emblem is too disruptive to the surface-level atmosphere of the site. I mean, we can probably all agree that it draws the eye, especially in contrast to the characteristically bleak design and color scheme of the rest of the site. It is out of place visually and when it comes to atmospheric narrative; while you can disagree, I don't think that the SCP Foundation, the cold, covert, ominous, bureaucratic, harsh, machine-like, single-minded, jackboots-on-the-ground, unemotional global organization whose only motives are contained within its name would feel so compelled to so visibly show solidarity or celebration during Pride Month. For the reasons stated, I think it would be best to either revert back to the original emblem or at least to not return to the rainbow background for next year's Pride Month.</p>
<p>It isn't a big deal, it just grabbed my attention and irked me upon entering the site for the first time this month. No, not for its message, but for how out-of-place and aesthetically disruptive on visual and atmospheric/narrative/immersive levels it is. But that's just my two cents.</p>

							</div>

								
