			<div class="content" id="post-content-3829217">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Following up on ooblex’s post, it’s important to note that The Foundation is a creative writing website that represents a wide variety of people, <strong>including people who do not appreciate the ideas behind pride month.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Those people can leave.</p>
<p>While I neither demand nor expect everyone to <em>actively</em> appreciate the existence of pride month, those who oppose its existence in <em>any</em> sense are people I have no desire to interact with within the constraints of this community. I don't want to read their articles. I don't want to read their posts. I don't want them to read <em>my</em> articles. I just want them to leave.</p>
<p>I deal with them enough on the outside; I don't need the stress of having to deal with them here.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I don’t remember a special logo for Black History Month or any other signifigant event. Why just this group?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Black History month is about familiarizing yourself with the history of African Americans; while there are parallels with pride month, it's not quite the same sentiment. The change in logo is a way of signaling to people in the LGBTQ community that this community is proud of its LGBTQ members, and open to including more.</p>
<p>More to the point being expressed: I think it's fair to take issue with the logo for breaking &quot;character&quot; (and I think it is fair to argue that the Foundation, &quot;in character&quot;, would not adopt this symbol &#8212; though your canon may vary!), but I also think there's significant value in expressing 'out-of-character' solidarity with LGBTQ communities, and that this value trumps any damage done to the verisimilitude of the site.</p>

							</div>

								
					
