<blockquote>
<p>This is a question of atmospheric, aesthetic, narrative, and immersive disruption. The sentiment behind the alleged disruption is only pertinent insofar as the question of whether or not said sentiment (and/or the alleged disruption itself) is disruptive to the overarching atmosphere, aesthetics, narrative, and/or immersive qualities of the site as a whole.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I suspect there are methods to alleviate this if it genuinely disrupts your reading experience; I would not be surprised to find there are multiple ways to read SCP pages without the header image (or, in fact, the header at all). In fact, pursuing these options will likely increase the quality of your experience (because they'll involve removing other distracting elements which might negatively impact your immersion &#8212; such as the sidebar).</p>
<p>I think, overall, the benefit of making it clear to the community that we're welcoming toward members of the LGBTQ community is of greater value than the maintenance of an already semi-broken immersive experience. Think of it like the Bat-Signal: Yeah, it's distracting and a little strange, but the benefit here is that you'll get a bunch of <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">Batmans</span> LGBTQ people to show up and <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">fight crime</span> write/read articles on the site.</p>

