			<div class="content" id="post-content-3829243">
									

<p>While I agree with your point that the only innate shared characteristic of the users that this site represents is some kind of appreciation of creative writing related to the admittedly somewhat nebulous SCP Foundation universe, and so the site as a whole (meaning, the &quot;skeleton&quot; or &quot;foundation&quot; with a lower-case &quot;f&quot; of the site, part of which is the banner at the top of every page on the site, including the emblem on that banner) should not be a platform for any view or idea other than that shared characteristic, I think it can be slippery to delve into arguments concerning whether people agree or disagree with the sentiment behind the emblem change. Again, I'm not saying you are wrong, just that arguments that are valid and sound that do not even take agreement or disagreement with the sentiment into account may fare better in the long run.</p>
<p>The background to the emblem should be left out next year if not removed this year even if every last user of the site agreed with the sentiment behind the background, in my opinion. Same goes for any other agenda-driven (agreeable agendas and disagreeable agendas alike) or non-agenda-driven but still disruptive change to the base platform of the site (like the top banner) that is not necessarily pertinent to all aspects of the SCP Foundation narrative universe, <strong>whether it be a rainbow background to the emblem on the top banner in celebration of Pride Month, an oblique reference to a specific non-Heritage SCP article, information on the migration routes of dolphins, instructions on how to tie a tie, a celebration of some real-world or non-baseline-canon event, or a clip art cheeseburger.</strong></p>

