			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3829256">
									

<p>I want to be part of a community with intellectual diversity that includes everyone, not just those like me. People who don't appreciate the ideas behind pride month are perfectly entitled to their opinions and feelings, but will have to live with the reality that the site admins made a call for a cause they support.</p>
<p>As for why this event and not others, the pressures of having to keep secrets for fear of rejection is a big factor in gender and sexuality issues. People identifying themselves openly is, to me, more about preventing people going through the same things from having to feel alone or ashamed than it is about confrontation with others who would reject us. It's doing a potential service to LGBT community members that far outweighs the potential harm caused to others who might be offended by their presence. I know it would have meant a lot to me as a younger person to have seen something like this here.</p>

