<blockquote>
<p>for a site about a cold and unemotional foundation that is supposed to contain paranormal/anomalous entities</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I would say &quot;This isn't that organisation, it's a writing site, that's not a valid critisism&quot;, but when we have our main page warning to sort-of include the site itself as part of the narrative (ditto for all of our Information pages, which are written primarily from an in-universe standpoint), I can understand the confusion regarding the in-universe justification for the logo change.</p>
<p>As much as I love the feel of the front-page warning and the tone it sets for the site, maybe it's best to do away with it and other flavorful in-universe elements and present the site itself solely as a writing website.</p>
<hr />
<p>Alternatively, perhaps next year we could reinforce the logo with a &quot;mission statement&quot; on the main page to justify the logo from an in-universe standpoint. Just because the SCP is cold and unemotionaal does not mean that they can't show support for LGTBQ personnel, and that could stand to be reflected in a visible way.</p>

